---
import DocsLayout from "../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../../../components/docs/CodeBlock.astro";

const toc = [
  { id: "when", label: "When to use it", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "how", label: "How to write it", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "emitted", label: "What gets emitted", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "resolution", label: "URL resolution", level: 2 as const },
  { id: "centering", label: "Centering is the consumer's job", level: 2 as const },
];
---

<DocsLayout
  title="CSS mask-image"
  description="A utility class mounts the SVG via mask-image and recolors it with currentColor. optical-center: auto on the same rule rewrites the underlying SVG and inlines it as a data: URI."
  toc={toc}
>
  <h2 id="when">When to use it</h2>
  <p>
    Pick this when the icon is delivered as a CSS mask — typically
    when you want every icon to inherit <code>currentColor</code> so
    the same class can render in any text color without per-icon
    variants.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>shadcn-style icon primitives.</li>
    <li>Tailwind <code>mask-utility</code> stacks.</li>
    <li>Anywhere an icon ships as a one-color mask on top of a colored background.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="how">How to write it</h2>
  <p>
    Mount the SVG via <code>mask</code>, paint it with
    <code>background</code>, and add
    <code>optical-center: auto</code> to the same rule. The
    rule's element <em>is</em> the icon — there's no wrapper here.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    filename="icons.css"
    lang="css"
    code={`.icon-play {
  display: inline-block;
  width: 24px;
  height: 24px;
  background: currentColor;
  mask: url('lucide-static/icons/play.svg') center / contain no-repeat;
  optical-center: auto;
}`}
  />

  <CodeBlock
    filename="Button.tsx"
    lang="tsx"
    code={`<button>
  <span className="icon-play" />
</button>`}
  />

  <h2 id="emitted">What gets emitted</h2>
  <p>
    The PostCSS plugin reads each <code>url('…svg')</code> in the rule,
    rasterizes the file, runs the centering pipeline, rewrites the
    SVG's <code>viewBox</code>, and inlines the result as a
    <code>data:image/svg+xml,…</code> URI in place of the original URL.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    filename="dist/icons.css"
    lang="css"
    code={`.icon-play {
  display: inline-block;
  width: 24px;
  height: 24px;
  background: currentColor;
  mask: url('data:image/svg+xml;utf8,…rewritten…') center / contain no-repeat;
  --optical-center: auto;
}`}
  />

  <p>Two things to notice:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>The shift lives in the mask asset.</strong> The data URI
      contains an SVG with its <code>viewBox</code> already corrected.
      The browser sees a flat, pre-shifted icon and does no runtime
      work.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>No positioning was emitted.</strong> Unlike the wrapper
      patterns, this rule doesn't pick up <code>display: flex</code> or
      <code>translate</code> — the perceptual shift is internal to the
      asset, so the element's position is entirely the consumer's
      layout concern. Drop it in a flex item, a grid cell, a button,
      anywhere.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="resolution">URL resolution</h2>
  <p>The plugin resolves URLs in this order:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><code>data:</code> URIs and absolute <code>http(s):</code> URLs are skipped.</li>
    <li>Any matching <code>aliases</code> prefix you configured gets expanded.</li>
    <li>Absolute paths and <code>./</code> / <code>../</code> paths resolve against the CSS file's directory.</li>
    <li>
      Bare specifiers like <code>lucide-static/icons/play.svg</code>
      go through Node's module resolution against the CSS file's
      directory. That makes installed npm icon packages work without
      alias config.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <CodeBlock
    filename="postcss.config.js"
    lang="js"
    code={`import opticalCenter from 'optical-center/postcss';

export default {
  plugins: [
    opticalCenter({
      aliases: {
        '@icons': '/abs/path/to/icons',
      },
    }),
  ],
};`}
  />

  <h2 id="centering">Centering is the consumer's job</h2>
  <p>
    Because this rule doesn't emit positioning, the element it
    targets needs to be centered however the surrounding layout
    normally centers things. Inside a flex parent, that's
    <code>justify-content</code> + <code>align-items</code> on the
    parent, or <code>margin: auto</code> on the child — both work
    because the mask's <code>viewBox</code> already carries the shift.
  </p>

  <aside class="callout callout--tip">
    <p class="callout-label">Composing with a wrapper directive</p>
    <p>
      You can put <code>optical-center: auto</code> on a wrapper class
      <em>and</em> use <code>.icon-play</code> as the child. The
      wrapper picks up <code>display: flex</code> + <code>margin: auto</code>
      on the child but no <code>translate</code> (no JSX scan match
      because the child is a <code>{`<span>`}</code>, not a tracked
      icon component) — and the shift comes from the mask data URI
      itself. The two layers compose cleanly.
    </p>
  </aside>
</DocsLayout>
